d out what people thought in English. Taking metaphors and images from the poetry of Geoffrey Chaucer, Arthurian romances, bird debates, sermons, handbooks of exempla, and medieval dramas, the book provides new and sometimes surprising readings of such familiar texts as the House of Fame and the Morte Darthur. KATHY CAWSEY is an Associate Professor in the Department of English at Dalhousie University in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismyMiddle English, 1100-1500. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChaucer.  aMalory.  anightingale.  aowl.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800100350?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800100350423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800100350/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles